When importing from Bugzilla using the JIRA Importers Plugin version 5.0.4, disabled user are imported into a group called bugzilla-import-disabled-users, but the accounts are still marked Active. In some cases they are also added to some default groups like jira-developers and jira-users.

This is with Atlassian JIRA (v5.2.4.1#846-sha1:7ae4d02)

{code}
		final String username = externalAttachment.getAttacher();
		User user = userProvider.getUser(username);
		if (user == null) {
			log.warn("User named %s not found. attaching to issue with currently logged in user instead", username);
			user = authenticationContext.getLoggedInUser();
		}

{code}

This warning should not be triggered for CSV (and AFAIK for Mantis). 
I think that the nicest way is to add a capability (boolean) for each importer controller class telling us whether given importers defines (and expects) attachers or not.

When I import multiple projects in the same JSON file, and all projects and custom fields already exist, and custom fields are not global, JSON import creates new custom field types rather than applying values to the existing one.

Consider the following JSON:

{code}
{
    "projects": [
        {
            "key": "PROJ1",
            "issues": [
                {
                    "externalId": "eid1",
                    "summary": "An issue in PROJ1.",
                    "reporter": "admin",
                    "assignee": "admin",
                    "issueType": "IssueType1",
                    "status": "Open",
                    "created": 1228402673000,
                    "updated": 1230467525000
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "key": "PROJ2",
            "issues": [
                {
                    "externalId": "eid2",
                    "summary": "An issue in PROJ2.",
                    "reporter": "admin",
                    "assignee": "admin",
                    "issueType": "IssueType2",
                    "status": "Closed",
                    "resolution": "Resolved",
                    "created": 1359638884000,
                    "updated": 1361795683000,
                    "resolutionDate": 1361795640000,
                    "customFieldValues": [
                        {
                            "fieldName": "Some Custom Field",
                            "fieldType": "com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:datepicker",
                            "value": "2013-02-01"
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}
{code}

Both projects (PROJ1 and PROJ2) already exist. The custom field ("Some Custom Field") already exists, and its configuration scheme specifies just PROJ2. Importing this JSON will create a new custom field of the same name (but new id) in global scope and assign the value to that new custom field rather than the existing custom field.

If that JSON were to contain only PROJ1, everything ok.

If that JSON were to contain only PROJ2, everything ok. The custom field value is assigned to the already configured custom field.

If I change the existing "Some Custom Field" custom field's configuration to have global scope, everything ok.

If I separate this out into two JSON files, containing only one project each, and import them separately, everything ok.

Log file says something like the following when importing issue eid2:
{code}
Custom field not found. Creating a new custom field for com.atlassian.jira.plugins.importer.external.beans.ExternalCustomField@c1aec96[id=Some Custom Field,name=Some Custom Field,typeKey=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:datepicker,searcherKey=<null>,valueMappingDefinition=<null>,valueSet=<null>]
{code}

My workaround is to set all my custom fields to have configuration of global scope, which is unfortunate but ok (I think). Splitting the file into separate projects doesn't work for me because I also have to create links between issues in different projects, and that seems to be possible only if both ends of the link are in the same file.

